  <h2>What is a training practice?</h2>
  <p>A training practice is an NHS GP surgery that has been assessed and approved to train doctors who are specialising in general practice. Being a training practice is a mark of quality — it means our facilities, clinical standards, and supervision have been independently assessed and meet the high standards required by NHS Education for Scotland (NES).</p>

  <h2>GP Specialty Trainees</h2>
  <p>GP Specialty Trainees (sometimes called GP Registrars) are <strong>fully qualified doctors</strong> who have already completed their medical degree and foundation training in hospital. They are now undertaking postgraduate specialist training to become GPs.</p>
  <p>During their placement at Scoonie, they carry out consultations with patients, prescribe medication, and provide the same range of care as our established GPs. Each trainee works under the close supervision of one of our GP Partners, who acts as their named clinical supervisor and is always available for support and guidance.</p>
  <p>GP trainees typically spend between six and twelve months with us as part of their training programme.</p>

  <h2>Medical students</h2>
  <p>We also welcome undergraduate medical students on clinical placements, usually from the University of St Andrews or the University of Dundee. Medical students may observe consultations or, with your agreement, carry out supervised consultations as part of their training.</p>
  <p>A qualified clinician is always present or immediately available when a student is involved in your care.</p>

  <h2>Your consent matters</h2>
  <p>Your involvement in training is always <strong>entirely voluntary</strong>. Before a trainee or student is involved in your consultation, you will be asked for your consent. You have every right to decline, and this will <strong>not affect your care in any way</strong>.</p>
  <p>If you would prefer not to see a trainee or have a student present, simply let our reception team know when you book your appointment, or tell the clinician at the start of your consultation. No explanation is needed.</p>

  <h2>How training benefits patients</h2>
  <p>Having trainees and students at the practice brings a number of benefits:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Additional clinicians</strong> — trainees provide extra appointment capacity, which can mean shorter waits</li>
    <li><strong>Longer appointments</strong> — training consultations often allow more time for discussion</li>
    <li><strong>Up-to-date knowledge</strong> — trainees bring the latest clinical training and evidence-based practice</li>
    <li><strong>Quality assurance</strong> — being a training practice means we are regularly reviewed against high educational and clinical standards</li>
    <li><strong>Investing in the future</strong> — by supporting training, you are helping to ensure there are enough GPs to care for communities like ours in the years ahead</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Supervision and standards</h2>
  <p>All trainees are supervised by experienced GP Partners who are accredited GP trainers. Our training activities are overseen by NHS Education for Scotland, and the practice is regularly assessed to ensure training standards are maintained.</p>
  <p>If you have any questions about our role as a training practice, please speak to a member of our team or <a href="/contact/get-in-touch/">get in touch</a>.</p>

